          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-0-1-1",
              "title": "The Real Estate System",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "15 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Introduction to the Real Estate System\n\nReal Estate is not just about buildings; it's a complex system interacting with the broader economy. It involves three major markets:\n\n1.  **Space Market**: Where landlords and tenants exchange the right to use physical space (Rent).\n2.  **Asset Market**: Where investors trade ownership of real estate assets (Cap Rates & Prices).\n3.  **Development Industry**: Which connects the two by adding new supply when asset prices justify construction costs.\n\n### The Feedback Loop\n\nChanges in the space market (e.g., rising rents due to high demand) lead to higher property values in the asset market. If values rise above construction costs, developers build more, eventually increasing supply and moderating rents."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "> **Key Concept**: The 'Asset Market' determines the *Cap Rate*, which is the yield investors demand for holding real estate risk."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Knowledge Check: The System",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "q1",
                      "text": "Which market determines the 'Cap Rate'?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Space Market",
                        "Asset Market",
                        "Development Industry"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Asset Market",
                      "explanation": "The Asset Market is where investors trade ownership, and prices (and thus yields/cap rates) are set based on risk and return expectations."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "q2",
                      "text": "What happens if property values rise above construction costs?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Developers stop building",
                        "Developers build more",
                        "Rents decrease immediately"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Developers build more",
                      "explanation": "When Value > Cost, it is profitable to build, triggering new supply from the Development Industry."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-0-1-2",
              "title": "Cap Rate Outlook",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Understanding Cap Rates\n\nThe Capitalization Rate (Cap Rate) is the fundamental metric of real estate pricing. It represents the ratio of Net Operating Income (NOI) to Property Asset Value.\n\n$$ Cap Rate = \\frac{NOI}{Value} $$\n\n### Macroeconomic Drivers\n\nCap rates are heavily influenced by the **Risk-Free Rate** (government bonds) and the **Risk Premium** specific to the property type and location."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Interactive Example\n\nUse the simulator below to see how changes in NOI and Cap Rate affect Property Value."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "PropertyValuationSimulator",
                  "props": {
                    "variant": "mini"
                  }
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "unit-0-2",
          "title": "Excel in Real Estate",
          "description": "Introductory course to Excel for Real Estate.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-0-2-1",
              "title": "Present Value Math",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "25 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Time Value of Money (TVM)\n\nMoney available at the present time is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its potential earning capacity. This core principle of finance holds that, provided money can earn interest, any amount of money is worth more the sooner it is received.\n\n### Key Formula: Present Value (PV)\n\n$$ PV = \\frac{FV}{(1 + r)^n} $$\n\nWhere:\n* **FV** = Future Value\n* **r** = Discount Rate\n* **n** = Number of periods"
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Excel Implementation\n\nIn Real Estate, we use Excel functions to calculate these values efficiently:\n* `=PV(rate, nper, pmt, [fv], [type])`\n* `=NPV(rate, value1, [value2], ...)`\n\n> **Tip**: Always assume cash flows occur at the *end* of the period unless stated otherwise."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "TVM Quiz",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "tvm-1",
                      "text": "If the discount rate increases, what happens to the Present Value (PV)?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Increases",
                        "Decreases",
                        "Stays the same"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Decreases",
                      "explanation": "A higher denominator (1+r) results in a smaller PV. Higher risk (rate) lowers today's value."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "tvm-2",
                      "text": "Which Excel function calculates the regular payment for a loan?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "=PV()",
                        "=PMT()",
                        "=FV()"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "=PMT()",
                      "explanation": "PMT calculates the payment for a loan based on constant payments and a constant interest rate."
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Hands-on Lab: Calculating PV in Excel\n\nUse the spreadsheet below to practice the PV formula."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "ExcelSimulator"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-0-2-2",
              "title": "Geltner Miller Ch 8",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "30 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Investment Value vs. Market Value\n\n**Investment Value** is specific to a particular investor based on their individual investment criteria (required yield, tax status, etc.).\n\n**Market Value** is the most probable price a property should bring in a competitive and open market."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Discussion Questions\n\n1. Why might an investor pay *more* than market value for a property?\n2. How does the 'marginal investor' determine the market clearing price?"
                }
              ],
              "contentUrl": "/content/real-estate-101/excel/reading.pdf"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "unit-0-3",
          "title": "Finance for Real Estate",
          "description": "Introduction to Finance principles.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-0-3-1",
              "title": "Asset Pricing Foundations",
              "type": "article",
              "duration": "20 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Risk and Return\n\nReal estate assets are priced based on the relationship between expected risk and required return. The **Risk-Free Rate** (typically government bonds) forms the baseline, to which a **Risk Premium** is added to compensate for illiquidity, leverage, and asset-specific risks."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Risk & Return Check",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "rr-1",
                      "text": "Which component of return is generally considered less risky?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Income Return",
                        "Appreciation Return"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Income Return",
                      "explanation": "Income comes from contractual leases, whereas appreciation depends on future market conditions and exit cap rates."
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "### Cap Rate Decomposition\n\n$ R = r_f + RP $\n\nWhere:\n* **R** = Required Return (Cap Rate)\n* **$r_f$** = Risk-Free Rate\n* **RP** = Risk Premium"
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "Asset Pricing Slides",
                  "type": "pptx",
                  "path": "/content/real-estate-101/finance/slides.pptx"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
