            {
              "id": "lesson-2-4",
              "title": "The Strategic Use of Debt",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Why Use Debt?\n\nBeyond simply lacking capital, investors use debt for three strategic reasons:\n\n1.  **Leverage (ROI)**: Unleveraged real estate has limited growth. Leverage transforms a 1% return impact into a 4% impact (at 75% LTV), attracting entrepreneurial talent.\n2.  **Diversification**: Debt allows spreading equity across more assets.\n    *   *Example*: €10m Equity.\n    *   Option A (All Cash): Buy **2** properties worth €5m each.\n    *   Option B (75% LTV): Buy **8** properties worth €5m each ($40m total). \n    *   *Result*: Reduced idiosyncratic risk.\n3.  **Inflation Hedge**: Fixed-rate debt payments stay flat while rental income rises with inflation (\"Reverse-inflation risk\")."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-5",
              "title": "Advanced Capital Stack",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Beyond Senior Debt\n\n### Mezzanine Debt\n*   **Structure**: Subordinate to Senior Debt, senior to Equity.\n*   **Security**: Often secured by a pledge of *equity interest* in the borrowing entity, not the property itself.\n*   **Rights**: Can foreclose on the entity (take over control) if detailed.\n\n### Preferred Equity\n*   **Nature**: Hybrid Instrument. Part of the ownership stack but behaves like debt (fixed return).\n*   **Priority**: Paid before Common Equity but after all Debt.\n*   **Control**: No operational control unless a \"Kick-out\" event occurs.\n\n### GP / LP Structure\n*   **Capital Partner (LP)**: Provides majority of cash (90-95%), limited control.\n*   **Entrepreneurial Partner (GP)**: Provides expertise, manages changes, receives **Promote** (Performance Fees)."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-2-3",
              "title": "Lecture Slides",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Key Takeaways\n\n*   **Positive Leverage**: When Cost of Debt < Cap Rate -> Increases Equity Returns.\n*   **Negative Leverage**: When Cost of Debt > Cap Rate -> Dilutes Equity Returns."
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "Capital Structures Slides",
                  "type": "pptx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-2/slides.pptx"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "unit-3",
          "title": "Commercial Mortgages",
          "description": "Analysis of mortgage structures.",
          "lessons": [
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-1",
              "title": "Mortgage Lab Simulator",
              "type": "simulator",
              "duration": "45 min",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Loan Mechanics Lab\n\nExplore how **Interest Rate**, **Amortization Period**, and **Loan-to-Value (LTV)** determine the debt service and payment schedule."
                },
                {
                  "type": "simulator",
                  "simulatorId": "MortgageMasterSimulator"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-2",
              "title": "Commercial Mortgages Slides",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Note vs. Mortgage\n\n*   **Promissory Note**: The contract detailing the financial obligation (Terms, Rate, Payment Schedule).\n*   **Mortgage (or Deed of Trust)**: The legal instrument pledging the property as collateral for the loan."
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "Intro to Mortgages Slides",
                  "type": "pptx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/slides.pptx"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-3",
              "title": "Underwriting Guide",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Lender's Criteria\n\nLenders primarily look at two ratios:\n\n1.  **Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)**: $\\frac{NOI}{Debt Service}$\n2.  **Loan-to-Value (LTV)**: $\\frac{Loan Amount}{Property Value}$"
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Underwriting Quiz",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "mtg-1",
                      "text": "What does a DSCR of 1.25x indicate?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "NOI is 25% higher than Debt Service",
                        "NOI is equal to Debt Service",
                        "NOI is less than Debt Service"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "NOI is 25% higher than Debt Service",
                      "explanation": "A DSCR > 1.0 means the property generates enough income to cover the loan payments with a safety margin."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "resources": [
                {
                  "title": "Underwriting & Default Slides",
                  "type": "pptx",
                  "path": "/content/refi/unit-3/underwriting.pptx"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-4",
              "title": "Adjustable Rate Mortgages (ARM)",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## How ARMs Work\n\nAn Adjustable Rate Mortgage (ARM) has an interest rate that changes periodically based on a financial index.\n\n### The Formula\n$$Interest Rate = Index + Margin$$\n\n*   **Index**: A benchmark rate (e.g., LIBOR, SOFR, 1-Year T-Bill).\n*   **Margin**: A fixed spread charged by the lender (e.g., 250 bps or 2.5%).\n\n### Interest Rate Caps\nTo protect borrowers from extreme volatility, ARMs have caps:\n1.  **Annual Cap**: Limit on how much the rate can change in one year.\n2.  **Lifetime Cap**: Limit on how high the rate can ever go.\n3.  **Payment Cap**: Limit on how much the monthly payment can increase (rare).\n\n### Example: Golden Horizons\n*   **Loan**: €1,000,000 (30-Year)\n*   **Initial Rate**: 6.0%\n*   **Index**: 5.5%\n*   **Margin**: 2.5%\n*   **Fully Indexed Rate**: 5.5% + 2.5% = **8.0%**\n\nIn this case, the borrower starts at 6%, but if the rate adjusts to the fully indexed rate of 8%, the payments will rise significantly."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "id": "lesson-3-5",
              "title": "Loan Analysis Cases",
              "type": "article",
              "sections": [
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Case 1: Valuing Seasoned Loans\n\nWhen a loan is sold in the secondary market (e.g., to a fund like Golden Horizon), its price is determined by the **Current Market Yield**, not the original interest rate.\n\n*   **Scenario**: 2 Years Old, 8% Coupon, 15-Year Term.\n*   **Market Yield**: 7.25% (Rates have fallen).\n*   **Result**: The loan will trade at a **Premium** (Price > Outstanding Loan Balance).\n\n### Prepayment Risk\nIf rates fall, borrowers are likely to prepay. If the loan was bought at a premium, prepayment results in a loss of yield for the investor. **Prepayment Penalties** (Yield Maintenance) are designed to protect against this."
                },
                {
                  "type": "markdown",
                  "content": "## Case 2: Refinancing Decisions\n\nBorrowers refinance when the savings from a lower interest rate outweigh the transaction costs (points, fees).\n\n### NPV Analysis Steps\n1.  Calculate current loan payment (Cost of Status Quo).\n2.  Calculate new loan payment + Closing Costs (Cost of Refi).\n3.  Compare the PV of savings over the holding period.\n\n> **Example**: Moving from 9% (Old) to 7% (New) + 2 Points fees.\n> If the holding period is short (e.g., 2 years), the fees might exceed the interest savings. If long (e.g., 10 years), refinancing is likely profitable."
                },
                {
                  "type": "quiz",
                  "content": "Unit 3 Assessment",
                  "quizData": [
                    {
                      "id": "u3-1",
                      "text": "Which Mortgage type has fixed, flat payments?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Interest-Only",
                        "Constant Payment Mortgage (CPM)",
                        "Constant Amortization Mortgage (CAM)",
                        "ARM"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Constant Payment Mortgage (CPM)",
                      "explanation": "CPM allows borrowers to pay the same amount every month, making budgeting easier."
                    },
                    {
                      "id": "u3-2",
                      "text": "How is the Principal Amortization calculated in a period?",
                      "type": "multiple-choice",
                      "options": [
                        "Interest Owed - Payment",
                        "Payment - Interest Owed",
                        "Loan Balance / Term"
                      ],
                      "correctAnswer": "Payment - Interest Owed",
                      "explanation": "The portion of the payment that exceeds the interest due goes towards reducing the principal."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
